  "texts": [
    "Unlike a standard autoencoder, a VAE's latent space is continuous and organized, allowing for more precise regulation of produced outputs and more natural interpolation between samples.",
    "This is very helpful in fields like drug design, where generating molecules with desired features is essential.",
    "In addition, they are more stable and simpler to train than GANs because they have a clearly defined optimization objective and avoid problems like mode collapse (it means the generator will only generate the most probable outputs it has found and will ignore the other modes present in the training data, resulting in a lack of variety in the produced samples.)",
    "and training instability.",
    "While models like GANs need a large training set to get reasonable results, VAEs may be made to learn in low-data regimes."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}